Nottingham Trent University (February 2024 - current)

I currently work as a Senior Lecturer in Psychology at Nottingham Trent University.

I teach various modules (“courses” in the US) including Lifespan Development, Research Methods, and Developing Academic Skills in Psychology.

I am part of the Language, Literacy, and Psycholinguistics Research Group.

My research interests are as follows:

  • psycholinguistics (bilingualism, skilled reading)
  • diversity, equity, and inclusion in the unrelated areas of open-source software development and the teaching of statistics
  • the incorporation of large language models into educational contexts

University of Nottingham (August 2022 - January 2024)

I was a Community Development Champion in the School of Psychology at the University of Nottingham in the United Kingdom. I worked exclusively with the team at Open Science Tools, Ltd. (the makers of the open-source software for psychological experiments PsychoPy, and its online sister Pavlovia). I was hired through funding from an Essential Open Source Software for Science grant from the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, obtained by the fun, friendly, upstanding team at PsychoPy. I am a Community Development Champion in the School of Psychology at the University of Nottingham in the United Kingdom. I work mostly with the team at Open Science Tools, Ltd. (the creators of the open-source software for psychological experiments PsychoPy, and its online sister Pavlovia. I was hired through funding from an Essential Open Source Software for Science grant from the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, obtained by the team at PsychoPy.

The first project I carried out was designing a survey in Pavlovia that was sent out both to members of the PsychoPy user forum and to researchers who had frequently cited PsychoPy in their publications. Here are the results.

I also organise various workshops and codesprints. One kind of workshop that I ran myself was the 3-hour translator workshops.
